const groups = [
  { id: "pwn", kicker: "Build the primitive", title: "Exploit Development & Pwn", items: [
    ["Arbitrary Object Directory Creation to LPE", "https://googleprojectzero.blogspot.com/2018/08/windows-exploitation-tricks-exploiting.html", "James Forshaw / Project Zero", "2018", 5, "object manager directory creation CSRSS AppContainer LPE Windows", "Turns an arbitrary object-manager directory creation bug into local privilege escalation by combining CSRSS behavior, namespace shadowing, symbolic links, and AppContainer-specific directories. The article is exemplary non-memory-corruption exploitation: each object and access check is developed explicitly until a constrained namespace primitive crosses a privilege boundary."],
    ["Symbolic Hooks Part 2: Getting the Target Name", "https://windows-internals.com/symhooks-part-two/", "Alex Ionescu", "2020", 5, "object manager symbolic link hook target name Windows exploitation", "Continues the Symbolic Hooks research by recovering the target of object-manager symbolic links and working through the internal name-resolution machinery required for a reliable hook. The series is valuable exploit-development material because it builds a primitive from namespace semantics and kernel objects rather than relying on code patching."],
    ["Symbolic Hooks Part 3: The Remainder Theorem", "https://windows-internals.com/symhooks-part-three/", "Alex Ionescu", "2020", 5, "symbolic hooks object manager parse procedure kernel redirection", "Develops the symbolic-link interception mechanism further by addressing unresolved parsing and redirection cases inside the object manager. It documents the constraints that emerge when a proof of concept meets real namespace behavior, making this installment essential for understanding the technique as a robust primitive rather than a novelty."],
    ["Symbolic Hooks Part 4: The App Container Traverse-ty", "https://windows-internals.com/symhooks-part-four/", "Alex Ionescu", "2020", 5, "symbolic hooks AppContainer object manager path traversal sandbox", "Applies the symbolic-hook model to AppContainer namespace traversal and shows how sandbox-specific path handling changes the reachable objects and redirection behavior. The article connects a low-level object-manager technique to an actual security boundary, while carefully examining the access checks and namespace layout that determine exploitability."],
    ["Exploiting a Simple Vulnerability in 35 Steps", "https://windows-internals.com/exploiting-a-simple-vulnerability-in-35-easy-steps-or-less/", "Yarden Shafir", "2020", 5, "Windows kernel exploitation arbitrary increment token privileges PreviousMode", "Begins with an intentionally modest kernel corruption primitive and develops it through the many constraints that real exploitation imposes, including address discovery, object selection, and privilege manipulation. The article is valuable precisely because it refuses to collapse the chain into token stealing and instead records the engineering decisions between trigger and reliable elevation."],
    ["Exploiting a Simple Vulnerability, Part 1.5: The Info Leak", "https://windows-internals.com/exploiting-a-simple-vulnerability-part-1-5-the-info-leak/", "Yarden Shafir", "2021", 5, "Windows kernel exploitation information leak KASLR object addresses", "Extends the simple-vulnerability series by constructing the information disclosure needed to make the later exploit deterministic. It separates the leak from the corruption primitive and demonstrates why modern kernel exploitation should account explicitly for object addresses and KASLR instead of assuming a convenient legacy disclosure API."],
    ["Exploiting a Simple Vulnerability, Part 2", "https://windows-internals.com/exploiting-a-simple-vulnerability-part-2-what-if-we-made-exploitation-harder/", "Yarden Shafir", "2021", 5, "Windows kernel exploitation mitigation bypass constrained primitive", "Revisits the same laboratory after deliberately removing convenient assumptions and adding exploitation constraints. Comparing the revised chain with the earlier solution shows how a primitive must be redesigned around mitigations, build behavior, and side effects, making the series useful practice for adapting rather than memorizing a single exploit."],
    ["One I/O Ring to Rule Them All", "https://windows-internals.com/one-i-o-ring-to-rule-them-all-a-full-read-write-exploit-primitive-on-windows-11/", "Yarden Shafir", "2022", 5, "Windows 11 I/O rings kernel arbitrary read write primitive", "Shows how corruption of I/O ring bookkeeping can transform a limited kernel write into a full kernel read/write primitive using legitimate asynchronous I/O machinery. The post documents the relevant user and kernel objects, registered-buffer path, and operational sequence in enough detail to understand both the exploit technique and its patch surface."],
    ["Windows Exploitation Tricks: Arbitrary File Writes", "https://googleprojectzero.blogspot.com/2018/04/windows-exploitation-tricks-exploiting.html", "James Forshaw / Project Zero", "2018", 5, "Windows LPE arbitrary file write oplock mount point hard link", "A foundational treatment of turning a constrained file-write vulnerability into local privilege escalation on modern Windows after earlier mount-point techniques were hardened. It carefully develops the object-manager and filesystem primitives, the race window, and the security boundary being crossed, so it remains a model for reasoning about non-memory-corruption exploits."],
    ["Windows Drivers Reverse Engineering Methodology", "https://voidsec.com/windows-drivers-reverse-engineering-methodology/", "VoidSec", "2022", 5, "WDM driver reversing IOCTL MSR MmMapIoSpace methodology", "A repeatable end-to-end methodology for lab setup, driver entry-point recovery, dispatch and IOCTL mapping, dangerous primitive discovery, and exploitability analysis. It includes a deliberately constrained target and exercises that force the reader to validate data flow rather than pattern-match vulnerable APIs."],
    ["Exploiting the System Mechanic driver", "https://voidsec.com/exploiting-system-mechanic-driver/", "VoidSec", "2021", 5, "driver reversing fuzzing token privileges LPE CTF", "Turns an initially unknown commercial driver into a complete exploitation exercise: interface recovery, fuzzing, root-cause analysis, primitive constraints, and SYSTEM escalation. It is especially valuable as a CTF-style Windows pwn writeup against a realistic third-party target."],
    ["CVE-2026-40369: Twelve Bytes to Escape the Browser Sandbox", "https://voidsec.com/cve-2026-40369-browser-sandbox-escape/", "VoidSec", "2026", 5, "Windows kernel arbitrary write sandbox escape NtCreateToken KASLR", "Develops a twelve-byte kernel write reachable from a browser renderer into SYSTEM without relying on classical token stealing. The chain disables the kernel-address-leak gate, locates the token, acquires token-creation privileges, and forges a SYSTEM primary token with unusually clear primitive accounting."],
    ["Crucial MOD Utility LPE (CVE-2021-41285)", "https://voidsec.com/crucial-mod-utility-lpe-cve-2021-41285/", "VoidSec", "2021", 5, "WinRing0 physical memory mapping driver LPE CVE-2021-41285", "Shows how a vendor utility inherited WinRing0's dangerous MSR and physical-memory functionality verbatim. The article combines binary comparison, IOCTL recovery, physical mapping, page-table reasoning, and a published exploit, making it a model driver-reuse case study."],
    ["Swimming in the (Kernel) Pool, Part 1", "https://connormcgarr.github.io/swimming-in-the-kernel-pool-part-1/", "Connor McGarr", "2021", 5, "HEVD pool exploitation, kLFH behavior, and low-integrity pool attacks", "Builds a Windows kernel pool exploit from allocator behavior upward, including an out-of-bounds read used for KASLR defeat. The careful treatment of kLFH makes it a strong foundation for understanding why heap shaping works rather than merely copying a spray."],
    ["ROP Gadget Hunting on Windows", "https://core-jmp.org/2026/06/rop-scanner-windows-rop-gadget-hunting-exploit-chain/", "core-jmp", "2026", 5, "ROP JOP gadgets CFG DEP VirtualProtect stack pivot", "Walks from instruction-pointer control to a bad-byte-clean VirtualProtect chain using ROP, JOP, syscall, and stack-pivot gadgets. It also considers CFG-aware gadget selection, making the article useful for designing a repeatable modern gadget-hunting workflow."],
    ["Exploiting the NT Kernel in 24H2", "https://exploits.forsale/24h2-nt-exploit/", "exploits.forsale", "2024", 5, "Windows 11 24H2 double fetch KASLR prefetch", "Covers bug discovery and exploit development against Windows 11 24H2, including double-fetch flaws introduced by user-memory handling changes. Its KASLR section connects prefetch timing with the reliability differences seen across Intel, AMD, native, and virtualized targets."],
    ["Physical-memory KASLR bypass on Windows 11 24H2", "https://xacone.github.io/kaslr_leak_24h2.html", "xacone", "2024", 5, "physical memory CR3 page tables HVCI KASLR", "Turns driver-assisted physical-memory access into a kernel-base disclosure after legacy pointer leaks were restricted. The post is an excellent practical reference for CR3 discovery, page-table traversal, and physical-to-virtual translation under HVCI."],
    ["From arbitrary pointer dereference to kernel R/W", "https://hnsecurity.it/blog/from-arbitrary-pointer-dereference-to-arbitrary-read-write-in-latest-windows-11/", "Hacking Notes", "2024", 5, "Windows 11 arbitrary pointer dereference SMEP kernel read write", "Develops a constrained arbitrary-pointer dereference into an arbitrary kernel read/write capability on a current Windows 11 target. The value lies in the intermediate reasoning: primitive refinement, SMEP constraints, and the choices needed to reach reliable privilege escalation."],
    ["Non-Paged Pool Overflow Exploitation", "https://github.com/vp777/Windows-Non-Paged-Pool-Overflow-Exploitation", "vp777", "2021", 4, "CVE-2020-17087 pool overflow off by one named pipe", "A hands-on collection for exploiting named-pipe non-paged-pool corruption, including CVE-2020-17087 and an off-by-one variant. It is useful for comparing allocator manipulation and exploitation techniques across older and newer Windows releases."],
    ["Shadow SSDT hijacking via R/W primitives", "https://www.exploitpack.com/blogs/news/shadow-ssdt-hijacking-to-achieve-kernel-code-execution-via-rw-primitives", "Exploit Pack", "2026", 4, "Shadow SSDT VBS HVCI kCET kernel execution", "Explores converting kernel read/write into code execution by targeting the Shadow SSDT while VBS, HVCI, and kernel CET are active. Treat it as a specialized chain-design study and validate assumptions against the exact Windows build you target."],
    ["HEVD SMEP bypass", "https://fluidattacks.com/blog/hevd-smep-bypass", "Fluid Attacks", "2020", 4, "HEVD SMEP bypass ROP kernel exploitation", "Introduces SMEP's effect on classic kernel shellcode execution and adapts an HEVD exploit to bypass it. The tutorial is especially useful as a bridge from older token-stealing exercises to ROP-based kernel exploitation."],
  ]},
  { id: "ctf", kicker: "Practice the full chain", title: "Windows CTF Pwn", items: [
    ["STAR Labs Windows Exploitation Challenge 2025", "https://starlabs.sg/blog/2025/03-star-labs-windows-exploitation-challenge-2025-writeup/", "STAR Labs / Võ Văn Tiến Dũng", "2025", 5, "Windows kernel CTF race condition UAF pool DQE arbitrary read write", "A complete solution to a purpose-built Windows kernel challenge centered on racing message buckets into a non-paged-pool use-after-free. It develops the corrupted object through buffered DQE reclamation and fake-object spraying into arbitrary kernel read/write, with enough structure recovery and timing detail to reproduce the reasoning."],
    ["HFSAntiCheat — Midnight Sun CTF Finals", "https://clubby789.me/hfsanticheat/", "clubby789", "2023", 5, "Windows kernel CTF KMDF anti-cheat IOCTL physical memory shellcode", "Reverses a KMDF anti-cheat driver, reconstructs its IOCTL surface, and works through a deliberately unusual kernel exploitation environment. The writeup is strong because it documents failed assumptions, WDF structure recovery, physical-memory constraints, and the final kernel payload rather than presenting only a solve script."],
    ["OpenDoor — HTB Business CTF 2022", "https://www.hackthebox.com/blog/open-door-business-ctf", "Hack The Box", "2022", 4, "Windows kernel CTF arbitrary read write EPROCESS token WinDbg", "An accessible Windows kernel challenge built around an intentionally backdoored driver exposing arbitrary read/write. It provides a clean laboratory for locating kernel modules and EPROCESS objects, walking ActiveProcessLinks, and replacing a token while learning the relevant WinDbg workflow."],
    ["Secure Storage Driver — CCCamp 2023", "https://ctftime.org/writeup/37751", "h4x0r-dz / CTFtime", "2023", 4, "Windows kernel CTF pool overflow IOCTL kernel read write", "A ring-0 Windows challenge writeup that begins with the supplied user-mode client and reverses the driver's IOCTL contract before exploiting a kernel pool corruption primitive. Its value is the concrete transition from interface reconnaissance to controlled kernel memory operations and a working exploit."],
    ["WkNote — SECCON CTF 2023 Finals", "https://ctftime.org/writeup/38357", "mephi42 / CTFtime", "2023", 4, "Windows kernel CTF note driver heap pool exploit", "A compact but code-backed solution to a Windows kernel note-driver pwnable from SECCON Finals. The linked exploit is the important artifact: it demonstrates kernel heap manipulation and the exact user-mode interactions needed to turn the challenge bug into privilege escalation."],
    ["FileUtility — Pflanzen CTF 2026", "https://unvariant.pages.dev/writeups/plfanzenctf-2026/die-braucht-viel-licht/", "unvariant", "2026", 5, "Windows kernel CTF file object handle driver exploitation", "A modern Windows kernel challenge whose driver consumes a user-supplied file handle and returns file metadata under subtle lifetime and object-manager constraints. The solution is valuable for its detailed exploration of Windows file objects, kernel handles, exploitation dead ends, and the stronger primitive ultimately constructed."],
    ["Reverse Engineering a Kernel Driver Challenge", "https://pwner.gg/blog/2024-09-22-kernel-driver-pwn", "pwner.gg", "2024", 4, "Windows driver challenge reversing bug PoC exploitation series", "A staged driver-pwn laboratory presented as a reversing and exploitation series: recover the interface, locate the vulnerability, build a trigger, then strengthen the primitive toward LPE. The article serves as the durable index while the accompanying videos preserve the live analysis process and mistakes."],
    ["Pwn2Own 2013 Windows kernel exploit", "https://labs.reversec.com/posts/2013/09/mwr-labs-pwn2own-2013-write-up-kernel-exploit", "MWR Labs", "2013", 5, "Pwn2Own Windows win32k pool overflow kernel fuzzer sandbox escape", "A classic but still instructive account of the win32k kernel stage used to escape Chrome's sandbox at Pwn2Own. It covers fuzzer discovery, root-cause analysis, pool layout control, exploit construction, and the mitigations of its era, making it useful historical context for how Windows kernel pwn matured."],
    ["ProcessFlipper — SekaiCTF 2024", "https://github.com/project-sekai-ctf/sekaictf-2024/tree/main/pwn/process-flipper", "Project Sekai CTF", "2024", 5, "Windows 11 kernel CTF anti-cheat driver LPE solution", "An expert Windows 11 kernel challenge inspired by commercial anti-cheat behavior and distributed with the driver, environment, and official solution. The repository preserves both challenge construction and exploit source, making it substantially more useful than a narrative writeup without artifacts."],
    ["InsoBug — Insomni'hack 2023", "https://itm4n.github.io/insomnihack-2023-insobug/", "itm4n", "2023", 5, "Windows RPC CTF impersonation WebClient NTLM relay service", "A meticulously documented Windows RPC challenge built around a realistic authentication and impersonation logic bug. The writeup reconstructs the service interface, RPC transport, WebClient behavior, token state, and exploit path while explaining why several obvious approaches fail."],
    ["Hexacon 2022 Hyper-V Challenge", "https://github.com/nneonneo/hexacon-2022", "nneonneo", "2022", 5, "Hyper-V CTF VM escape VMBus reverse engineering exploit", "A complete solution artifact for Hexacon's Windows Hyper-V escape challenge, including tooling and exploit code. It is high-value practice for reverse engineering host/guest communication, reconstructing undocumented protocols, and chaining a virtual-device bug across the VM trust boundary."],
    ["Archangel Michael's Storage — HITCON CTF 2020", "https://github.com/scwuaptx/CTF/tree/master/2020-writeup/hitcon/MichaelStorage", "AngelBoy", "2020", 5, "Windows usermode CTF segment heap exploitation", "An advanced Windows user-mode heap challenge and solution focused on the segment heap rather than the classic NT heap. The source-backed writeup is useful for allocator state reconstruction, heap grooming, and studying exploitation techniques that are underrepresented in general pwn material."],
    ["Lucifer — HITCON CTF 2020", "https://github.com/scwuaptx/CTF/tree/master/2020-writeup/hitcon/lucifer", "AngelBoy", "2020", 5, "Windows kernel CTF segment heap driver exploitation", "A Windows kernel challenge designed around the kernel segment heap, with challenge and exploit artifacts preserved together. It provides rare hands-on material for understanding allocator metadata and grooming on builds where older pool exploitation recipes no longer describe reality."],
    ["BitmapManager — Dragon CTF 2020", "https://github.com/j00ru/ctf-tasks/tree/master/Dragon%20CTF%202020/BitmapManager", "j00ru / Dragon Sector", "2020", 5, "Windows kernel CTF bitmap manager driver challenge solution", "A professionally authored Windows kernel pwnable distributed with source, binaries, deployment material, and solution artifacts. It is a strong target for practicing driver attack-surface recovery and exploit construction against a challenge designed by an experienced Windows vulnerability researcher."],
  ]},
  { id: "mitigations", kicker: "Understand the boundary", title: "Mitigations & Windows Internals", items: [
    ["DUT Processes in Windows 10", "https://windows-internals.com/dut-processes-in-windows-10/", "Alex Ionescu and Yarden Shafir", "2020", 5, "DUT process Windows protection level secure process trust model", "Investigates the undocumented DUT process category and places it within Windows' evolving protected-process and trust model. By recovering creation policy, flags, and kernel checks, the post illustrates how security-sensitive process classes differ from ordinary PPL labels and why precise terminology matters when evaluating process protection boundaries."],
    ["Random Windows Things: PreviousMode Mitigation", "https://windows-internals.com/random-windows-things-part-1-previousmode-mitigation/", "Yarden Shafir", "2026", 5, "PreviousMode Windows kernel mitigation KTHREAD exploit primitive hardening", "Examines Microsoft's newer hardening around the KTHREAD PreviousMode field, a long-standing target for turning kernel writes into trusted kernel-mode system-call behavior. It traces the implementation changes and their consequences for exploit chains, providing current context for why older PreviousMode recipes no longer transfer unchanged to recent builds."],
    ["Goodbye Secure Pool, Hello KDP Pool", "https://windows-internals.com/goodbye-secure-pool-hello-kdp-pool/", "Yarden Shafir", "2026", 5, "KDP pool secure kernel VTL1 memory integrity mitigation", "Documents the evolution from the original Secure Pool design to a KDP-backed pool mechanism for protecting sensitive kernel allocations. The analysis connects allocator behavior, VTL boundaries, access policy, and compatibility tradeoffs, making it a useful current reference for researchers evaluating which kernel data can still be modified from VTL0."],
    ["Module Tampering Protection", "https://windows-internals.com/understanding-a-new-mitigation-module-tampering-protection/", "Yarden Shafir", "2022", 5, "module tampering protection MTP Windows kernel image integrity", "Reverse engineers Module Tampering Protection as introduced in Windows, explaining the policy, loader integration, protected regions, and enforcement path rather than relying on the feature name. The post is particularly useful for distinguishing this mechanism from PatchGuard, HVCI, and ordinary image-signature checks when modeling kernel code-integrity boundaries."],
    ["HyperGuard Part 1: SKPG Initialization", "https://windows-internals.com/hyperguard-secure-kernel-patch-guard-part-1-skpg-initialization/", "Yarden Shafir", "2022", 5, "HyperGuard SKPG secure kernel PatchGuard VTL1 initialization", "The first part of a detailed HyperGuard reconstruction, following Secure Kernel Patch Guard initialization and the handoff of protected state into VTL1. It provides the vocabulary and lifecycle needed to reason about later extents and checks, while clearly separating hypervisor-enforced protection from traditional PatchGuard behavior in the normal kernel."],
    ["HyperGuard Part 2: SKPG Extents", "https://windows-internals.com/hyperguard-secure-kernel-patch-guard-part-2-skpg-extents/", "Yarden Shafir", "2022", 5, "HyperGuard SKPG extents secure kernel protected memory", "Continues the HyperGuard analysis by decoding SKPG extents, the descriptors that identify memory and state subject to secure-kernel validation. The article ties recovered structures to initialization and checking code, enabling researchers to verify precisely what is covered rather than treating HyperGuard as an undocumented monolithic integrity feature."],
    ["HyperGuard Part 3: More SKPG Extents", "https://windows-internals.com/hyperguard-part-3-more-skpg-extents/", "Yarden Shafir", "2022", 5, "HyperGuard SKPG extents callbacks MSR control registers", "Expands the extent taxonomy with additional protected targets and validation forms, including state that cannot be described as a simple immutable memory range. Read with the first two parts, it becomes an unusually complete public model of how Windows delegates sensitive kernel integrity checks across the VTL boundary."],
    ["Secure Pool Internals: Dynamic KDP", "https://windows-internals.com/secure-pool/", "Yarden Shafir", "2020", 5, "Secure Pool dynamic KDP VBS VTL1 kernel data protection", "Reverse engineers Secure Pool and Dynamic Kernel Data Protection from allocation request through secure-kernel enforcement. It explains how selected kernel data becomes read-only to ordinary VTL0 code while remaining manageable through controlled interfaces, giving exploit developers and defenders a concrete model of data protection under VBS."],
    ["R.I.P ROP: CET Internals in Windows", "https://windows-internals.com/cet-on-windows/", "Yarden Shafir", "2020", 5, "CET shadow stack Windows kernel user mode ROP mitigation", "A foundational implementation-level analysis of Intel CET support in Windows, covering shadow stacks, process policy, context switching, exception handling, and kernel participation. It goes well beyond a mitigation overview and explains the structures and transitions that determine whether return-address corruption is actually prevented."],
    ["CET Updates: CET on Xanax", "https://windows-internals.com/cet-updates-cet-on-xanax/", "Yarden Shafir", "2020", 5, "CET relaxed mode compatibility shadow stack Windows", "Examines Windows' compatibility mechanisms for applications that cannot immediately obey strict shadow-stack semantics, including relaxed handling and policy transitions. The details are important for security analysis because they reveal where deployment compatibility changes the effective protection promised by CET on paper."],
    ["CET Updates: Dynamic Address Ranges", "https://windows-internals.com/cet-updates-dynamic-address-ranges/", "Yarden Shafir", "2021", 5, "CET dynamic code JIT shadow stack address ranges mitigation", "Explains how Windows accommodates JIT engines and other dynamic-code producers under CET using managed address ranges and explicit policy. The article maps the supporting APIs and kernel bookkeeping, helping researchers distinguish legitimate dynamically generated call targets from gaps or abuse opportunities in shadow-stack enforcement."],
    ["The KASLR graveyard: leaking ntoskrnl on Windows 11 25H2", "https://afflicted.sh/blog/posts/kaslr-graveyard.html", "afflicted.sh", "2026", 5, "Windows 11 25H2 KASLR leaks GDT IDT desktop heap prefetch", "Tests a wide catalog of kernel-base disclosure paths against a concrete Windows 11 25H2 target and explains why each succeeds or fails. The result works like a modern KASLR decision tree spanning restricted queries, descriptor tables, desktop heaps, physical memory, CPU differences, and prefetch behavior."],
    ["Bypassing Windows Kernel Mitigations: Part 0", "https://hackyboiz.github.io/2025/04/13/l0ch/bypassing-kernel-mitigation-part0/en/", "Hackyboiz / L0ch", "2025", 5, "Windows 11 24H2 KASLR prefetch EntryBleed KVA shadow", "Explains the Windows 11 24H2 KASLR restriction from an exploit developer's perspective, then adapts an EntryBleed-style prefetch timing side channel. It connects page tables, KVA shadowing, TLB state, and CPU-specific timing behavior to practical ntoskrnl-base recovery."],
    ["Windows Exploit Mitigations", "https://github.com/nccgroup/exploit_mitigations/blob/main/windows_mitigations.md", "NCC Group", "Living", 5, "Windows mitigations DEP ASLR CFG CET reference", "A maintained knowledge base that maps Windows exploit mitigations to their purpose, scope, and implementation context. Use it as a high-level map before diving into a single bypass or comparing protections across platform generations."],
    ["KASLR Leaks Restriction", "https://windows-internals.com/kaslr-leaks-restriction/", "Windows Internals", "2024", 5, "ExIsRestrictedCaller NtQuerySystemInformation KASLR", "Explains the Windows changes that remove many kernel-address disclosures from unprivileged callers. It is the best starting point for understanding ExIsRestrictedCaller, affected system-information classes, and why older disclosure assumptions no longer hold."],
    ["An End to KASLR Bypasses?", "https://windows-internals.com/an-end-to-kaslr-bypasses/", "Windows Internals", "2024", 4, "kernel pointers restricted caller integrity level", "Provides the broader design context behind Microsoft's restriction of kernel pointer disclosures. It helps connect integrity levels and sandbox boundaries to the mitigation and identifies assumptions embedded in older Windows kernel exploits."],
    ["Windows Kernel Shadow Stack Mitigation", "https://www.synacktiv.com/sites/default/files/2025-06/sstic_windows_kernel_shadow_stack_mitigation.pdf", "Synacktiv / SSTIC", "2025", 5, "kernel shadow stack CET mitigation PDF", "A deep technical treatment of Windows kernel shadow stacks and their consequences for control-flow hijacking. The slides are dense but valuable when evaluating which exploitation paths kernel CET removes and what remains available."],
    ["The new Windows Component Filter mitigation", "https://big5-sec.github.io/posts/component-filter-mitigation/", "BIG5", "2024", 5, "Windows Component Filter kernel mitigation KASLR", "Reverse engineers the Component Filter mitigation and explains how Windows restricts sensitive system information by caller context. Read it alongside the KASLR restriction posts to understand both policy and implementation details."],
    ["Intel VT-rp, Part 1", "https://tandasat.github.io/blog/2023/07/05/intel-vt-rp-part-1.html", "Tandasat", "2023", 5, "Intel VT remapping HLAT KDP g_CiOptions", "Introduces a virtualization-based remapping attack and the role of Hypervisor-managed Linear Address Translation. It demonstrates how page-remapping ideas interact with KDP and g_CiOptions, connecting hardware virtualization to Windows kernel protection research."],
    ["Windows Internals archive", "https://windows-internals.com/category/windows-internals/", "Winsider", "Living", 5, "Windows internals kernel secure kernel VBS", "A concentrated archive of original Windows internals research spanning the kernel, secure kernel, mitigations, and low-level APIs. Use it as a topic index and favor the individual articles when recording a technique or claim."],
  ]},
  { id: "evasion", kicker: "Observe and evade", title: "Evasion & EDR", items: [
    ["Qilin EDR Killer Infection Chain", "https://blog.talosintelligence.com/qilin-edr-killer/", "Cisco Talos", "2026", 5, "Qilin EDR killer ETW syscalls kernel object manipulation hooks", "A code-level analysis of an EDR-killing DLL deployed with Qilin ransomware, covering its PE loader, SEH and VEH control-flow obfuscation, syscall and API resolution, user-mode hook removal, ETW suppression, and kernel-object manipulation. The report is especially useful because it follows the whole execution chain and relates each evasion layer to observable behavior."],
    ["DKOM, Now with Symbolic Links", "https://windows-internals.com/dkom-now-with-symbolic-links/", "Yarden Shafir", "2020", 5, "DKOM object manager symbolic links kernel hiding manipulation", "Demonstrates Direct Kernel Object Manipulation against object-manager symbolic links and uses the exercise to expose the structures and lookup behavior behind familiar DOS-device paths. Beyond the hiding effect, the post is a strong example of deriving a manipulation from object lifetime and namespace internals rather than copying offsets."],
    ["Kernel Data Discovery Through Lookaside Lists", "https://windows-internals.com/lookaside-list-forensics/", "Yarden Shafir", "2020", 5, "kernel data discovery lookaside lists forensics rootkit signature scanning", "Proposes lookaside-list metadata as a more structural way to discover kernel allocations than fragile byte signatures. The approach is relevant to both stealth tooling and memory forensics because it reasons from allocator ownership and cached object types, while also documenting the version and lifecycle assumptions a detector must validate."],
    ["RedEdr", "https://github.com/dobin/RedEdr", "dobin", "Living", 5, "EDR introspection ETW ETW-TI Defender telemetry hooks callbacks", "An open-source laboratory for observing the same Windows telemetry surfaces that endpoint products consume, including ETW, ETW Threat Intelligence, user-mode hooks, kernel callbacks, and Defender-specific providers. It earns a place here because it supports measurement and validation: researchers can see which behavior generated which signal instead of assuming that a bypass worked because a payload executed."],
    ["EDR-Introspection", "https://github.com/yo-yo-yo-jbo/EDR-Introspection", "John Barak", "Living", 5, "EDR internals minifilter callbacks ETW WFP telemetry enumeration", "A research tool for enumerating the operating-system integrations used by endpoint products, including process and object callbacks, minifilters, ETW providers, WFP filters, and related kernel registrations. It is especially useful for building a product-specific attack-surface map before testing evasion claims, and for comparing what remains visible after a technique changes one telemetry path."],
    ["libelevate: handle elevation against ObRegisterCallbacks", "https://github.com/notscimmy/libelevate", "notscimmy", "2017", 4, "ObRegisterCallbacks DKOM handle table access elevation anti-cheat EDR", "A compact kernel research project that bypasses access stripping by modifying a target handle-table entry after callbacks have run, rather than removing the callback registration itself. The accompanying explanation is valuable for studying ExEnumHandleTable, encoded handle entries, and the distinction between disabling an enforcement mechanism and repairing the rights it removed."],
    ["About Hiding on Windows", "https://kernullist.github.io/kernullist-blog/posts/hiding-on-windows/", "Kernullist", "2026", 5, "DKOM injection BYOVD hiding cross-view detection", "Surveys hiding processes, threads, DLLs, drivers, callbacks, and executable regions using DKOM, injection, and BYOVD techniques. Its cross-view detection discussion is particularly useful because it pairs offensive manipulation with the defender's competing sources of truth."],
    ["Attacking EDRs Part 1: EDR Drivers", "https://labs.infoguard.ch/posts/edr_part1_intro_-_security_analysis_of_edr_drivers/", "InfoGuard Labs", "2025", 5, "EDR driver callbacks attack surface reverse engineering", "Establishes a methodology for analyzing the kernel drivers that give EDR products visibility and enforcement power. It maps callbacks, exposed interfaces, and attack surface so later bypass work is grounded in how the product actually collects telemetry."],
    ["awesome-edr-bypass", "https://github.com/tkmru/awesome-edr-bypass", "tkmru", "Living", 4, "EDR bypass curated research tools", "A curated directory of EDR bypass research, techniques, presentations, and tooling. It is best used as a discovery index; verify individual techniques against modern product versions before treating them as operationally current."],
    ["KernelCallbackTable Injection PoC", "https://github.com/0xHossam/KernelCallbackTable-Injection-PoC#introduction", "0xHossam", "2024", 4, "process injection PEB KernelCallbackTable execution hijack", "Demonstrates process injection by replacing a callback pointer in the target's PEB-backed KernelCallbackTable. The compact PoC makes the execution flow easy to trace and provides a useful basis for studying telemetry and defensive detection."],
    ["kurasagi: runtime PatchGuard bypass", "https://github.com/NeoMaster831/kurasagi", "NeoMaster831", "2025", 4, "Windows 11 PatchGuard bypass 24H2 25H2", "A research implementation targeting runtime PatchGuard bypass on Windows 11 24H2 and 25H2. Because it depends strongly on undocumented and build-specific behavior, use it as an advanced study target rather than a portable technique."],
    ["BYOVD and legitimate certificates", "https://blog.ghostwolflab.com/apt/737/", "Ghost Wolf Lab", "2026", 3, "BYOVD APT certificates vulnerable drivers", "Discusses how BYOVD tradecraft is shifting from obviously vulnerable drivers toward trust inherited from legitimate certificates. It is a useful threat-research perspective for connecting driver abuse, signing policy, and the limits of blocklist-only defenses."],
  ]},
  { id: "byovd", kicker: "Cross the trust boundary", title: "BYOVD & Kernel Driver Abuse", items: [
    ["Exploring vulnerable Windows drivers", "https://blog.talosintelligence.com/exploring-vulnerable-windows-drivers/", "Cisco Talos", "2024", 5, "BYOVD arbitrary memory write MSR EDR ransomware driver blocklist", "One of the strongest modern surveys of how vulnerable drivers are converted into token theft, unsigned kernel-code loading, EDR termination, and destructive payloads. It joins vulnerability classes to real ransomware campaigns and explains where Microsoft's vulnerable-driver blocklist helps—and where it does not."],
    ["Signed kernel drivers: an unguarded gateway to Windows' core", "https://www.welivesecurity.com/2022/01/11/signed-kernel-drivers-unguarded-gateway-windows-core/", "ESET Research", "2022", 5, "BYOVD signed drivers DSE malware rootkit kernel", "A foundational study of signed-driver abuse across APT and commodity malware, supported by a large-scale survey of vulnerable drivers. It gives the historical and architectural context needed to understand why code signing alone cannot solve BYOVD."],
    ["LOLDrivers", "https://www.loldrivers.io/", "Community project", "Living", 5, "BYOVD hashes certificates vulnerable malicious drivers detection", "The canonical community-maintained catalog of Windows drivers abused to bypass security controls or execute kernel code. Each record connects hashes, signatures, known abuse, detections, and references, making it the first stop for triage—not a substitute for reversing the actual driver."],
    ["Shedding light on the ABYSSWORKER driver", "https://www.elastic.co/security-labs/abyssworker", "Elastic Security Labs", "2025", 5, "malicious driver EDR killer callbacks minifilter IOCTL ransomware", "A code-level analysis of the MEDUSA-linked ABYSSWORKER driver, including IOCTL handlers that terminate processes, remove callbacks, detach minifilters, and replace dispatch routines. RVAs, samples, YARA, and a client implementation make the research unusually reproducible."],
    ["Lazarus & BYOVD: evil to the Windows core", "https://www.welivesecurity.com/2022/09/30/amazon-themed-campaigns-lazarus-netherlands-belgium/", "ESET Research", "2022", 5, "Lazarus CVE-2021-21551 Dell driver rootkit EDR blinding", "Documents Lazarus weaponizing Dell's DBUtil vulnerability to obtain kernel read/write and disable monitoring components. It is a high-value bridge between exploit primitives and a real APT's operational rootkit and defense-evasion design."],
    ["Screwed Drivers", "https://github.com/eclypsium/Screwed-Drivers", "Eclypsium", "2019", 5, "signed drivers firmware access kernel primitives research corpus", "The research corpus behind Eclypsium's discovery of widespread signed drivers exposing privileged hardware and firmware access. It is useful both as a historic BYOVD turning point and as a concrete collection for comparing vulnerable interface patterns across vendors."],
    ["physmem_drivers", "https://github.com/namazso/physmem_drivers", "namazso", "Living", 5, "physical memory vulnerable signed drivers comparative library", "A compact comparative library for signed drivers that expose physical-memory primitives, with common abstractions and per-driver implementations. Reading the code side by side reveals how recurring IOCTL and mapping designs can be normalized into reusable kernel read/write capabilities."],
    ["KDU", "https://github.com/hfiref0x/KDU", "hfiref0x", "Living", 5, "kernel driver utility vulnerable driver providers DSE mapping", "A mature research utility with a provider model covering many vulnerable-driver families and multiple kernel-code loading strategies. Its breadth and careful build-specific handling make it executable documentation of the BYOVD ecosystem, though it belongs only in isolated research environments."],
    ["BYOVD Research", "https://github.com/KOSEC-LLC/BYOVD-Research", "KOSEC", "Living", 4, "BYOVD driver research exploit chains vendor analysis", "A focused repository collecting reproducible vulnerable-driver research and exploitation artifacts. It is valuable as a bridge from catalog records to code-level validation, with enough context to compare driver primitives rather than treating hashes as the research endpoint."],
    ["BlackSnufkin BYOVD", "https://github.com/BlackSnufkin/BYOVD", "BlackSnufkin", "Living", 4, "BYOVD EDR termination callbacks kernel driver PoC", "A practical implementation of vulnerable-driver-assisted security-product tampering with clear source and operational flow. Use it to study how user-mode orchestration, device IOCTLs, process discovery, and kernel capabilities are assembled into an EDR-kill chain."],
    ["RealBlindingEDR", "https://github.com/myzxcg/RealBlindingEDR", "myz", "2024", 5, "EDR callbacks minifilters ETW Ti vulnerable driver kernel tampering", "A source-level implementation of blinding EDR telemetry through kernel read/write, including callback, minifilter, and ETW-related targets. It is frequently referenced by threat research because it connects generic BYOVD primitives to the exact kernel structures defenders depend on."],
  ]},
  { id: "ipc", kicker: "Map privileged conversations", title: "COM, RPC & ALPC", items: [
    ["Calling Local Windows RPC Servers from .NET", "https://googleprojectzero.blogspot.com/2019/12/calling-local-windows-rpc-servers-from.html", "James Forshaw / Project Zero", "2019", 5, "Windows local RPC .NET NDR client generation UAC bypass", "Introduces Project Zero's .NET RPC tooling by parsing local server metadata, generating strongly typed clients, selecting endpoints and authentication, and exercising a real UAC bypass from PowerShell. It turns opaque NDR interfaces into callable research targets while preserving enough protocol detail to understand what the generated client is doing."],
    ["Injecting Code into Windows Protected Processes Using COM, Part 1", "https://googleprojectzero.blogspot.com/2018/10/injecting-code-into-windows-protected.html", "James Forshaw / Project Zero", "2018", 5, "COM PPL protected process code integrity KnownDlls injection", "Builds the background and first half of a Protected Process Light injection chain from Windows code-integrity policy, KnownDll handling, COM activation, and trust-level behavior. Paired with the follow-up exploit, it is one of the clearest demonstrations of COM as a security-boundary mechanism rather than merely an application automation technology."],
    ["Investigating Filter Communication Ports", "https://windows-internals.com/investigating-filter-communication-ports/", "Yarden Shafir", "2023", 5, "minifilter communication ports Filter Manager IPC security descriptors", "Reverse engineers the communication mechanism between filesystem minifilters and user-mode services, including Filter Manager port objects, connection state, messages, and access control. It fills an important IPC gap left by COM/RPC/ALPC material and provides a practical basis for auditing privileged filter services and their trust assumptions."],
    ["Offensive Windows IPC Internals 3: ALPC", "https://csandker.io/2022/05/24/Offensive-Windows-IPC-3-ALPC.html", "Christoph Sandker", "2022", 5, "ALPC ports messages attributes impersonation mapped views heap spray", "A systematic explanation of ALPC port relationships, message flow, attributes, security descriptors, impersonation, and resource-lifetime attack surface. It includes a working client/server laboratory and concrete methods for finding accessible ports and vulnerable high-privilege servers."],
    ["Debugging and Reversing ALPC", "https://csandker.io/2022/05/29/Debugging-And-Reversing-ALPC.html", "Christoph Sandker", "2022", 5, "ALPC WinDbg kernel debugging port objects reversing", "A practical companion that traces ALPC from user-mode calls into kernel objects with WinDbg. Read it after the IPC overview to learn how to verify undocumented behavior rather than relying on diagrams or stale structure definitions."],
    ["Injecting code into Windows Protected Processes using COM", "https://googleprojectzero.blogspot.com/2018/11/injecting-code-into-windows-protected.html", "James Forshaw / Project Zero", "2018", 5, "COM PPL protected process IDispatch ALPC injection", "Shows how COM marshaling and exposed automation interfaces can become an injection path into Protected Process Light targets. The research is exemplary because it develops the object and transport mechanics, exploit constraints, and mitigations rather than presenting COM as a registry trick."],
    ["Windows Exploitation Tricks: Relaying DCOM Authentication", "https://googleprojectzero.blogspot.com/2021/10/windows-exploitation-tricks-relaying.html", "James Forshaw / Project Zero", "2021", 5, "DCOM Kerberos relay OXID resolver RPC ALPC authentication", "Dissects DCOM activation, OXID resolution, RPC bindings, and authentication to construct a local Kerberos relay primitive. It is required reading for understanding the protocol machinery behind coercion and relay families instead of treating them as opaque Potato variants."],
    ["OleView.NET", "https://github.com/tyranid/oleviewdotnet", "James Forshaw", "Living", 5, "COM RPC inspection activation marshaling security tooling", "A comprehensive .NET suite for enumerating, inspecting, activating, and security-testing COM and RPC infrastructure. Its parsers, viewers, scripting model, and database make it both a daily research tool and executable documentation of COM internals."],
    ["Offensive Windows IPC Internals 2: RPC", "https://csandker.io/2021/02/21/Offensive-Windows-IPC-2-RPC.html", "Christoph Sandker", "2021", 5, "RPC interfaces endpoints authentication impersonation attack surface", "Builds an offensive mental model of Windows RPC from interface definitions and bindings through authentication and impersonation. It is particularly useful before COM research because it exposes the transport and server assumptions that COM normally hides."],
  ]},
  { id: "execution", kicker: "Follow execution into memory", title: "APC, Loaders & Injection", items: [
    ["Thread and Process State Change", "https://windows-internals.com/thread-and-process-state-change/", "Yarden Shafir", "2021", 5, "NtChangeProcessState NtChangeThreadState process thread state objects", "Investigates the newer process and thread state-change objects and the native APIs that operate on them, tracing their kernel implementation and supported actions. The article provides rare documentation for mechanisms that influence suspension, resumption, and process lifecycle outside the familiar Win32 wrappers, which is useful for both tooling and telemetry research."],
    ["Deferred Procedure Waits in Windows", "https://windows-internals.com/dpws-are-the-new-dpcs-deferred-procedure-waits-in-windows-10-21h1/", "Yarden Shafir", "2020", 5, "deferred procedure waits DPW DPC Windows kernel scheduling", "Introduces Deferred Procedure Waits from their undocumented structures and scheduler paths, contrasting them with conventional DPC execution. The research is useful for understanding new kernel execution contexts, synchronization semantics, and the forensic or security implications of work that does not fit older DPC-centric mental models."],
    ["APC Series: User APC API", "https://repnz.github.io/posts/apc/user-apc/", "Ori Damari / repnz", "2020", 5, "APC QueueUserAPC NtQueueApcThread alertable waits", "The correct entry point to a three-part APC series, establishing delivery rules, alertable waits, queueing APIs, and observable behavior. It replaces the usual copy-paste injection explanation with a precise execution model that remains useful for both offensive code and detection."],
    ["APC Series: User APC Internals", "https://repnz.github.io/posts/apc/kernel-user-apc-api/", "Ori Damari / repnz", "2020", 5, "KAPC KiDeliverApc kernel user APC internals", "Reverse engineers the kernel path behind user APC objects, queueing, state transitions, and delivery to user mode. This is the piece to read when an APC PoC behaves differently across thread states and you need to reason from kernel implementation rather than API documentation."],
    ["APC Series: KiUserApcDispatcher and WoW64", "https://repnz.github.io/posts/apc/wow64-user-apc/", "Ori Damari / repnz", "2020", 5, "KiUserApcDispatcher WoW64 APC injection Heaven's Gate", "Explains the dispatcher calling convention, NtContinue loop, and the 32/64-bit compatibility machinery used to deliver APCs into WoW64 processes. The cross-architecture injection analysis is unusually detailed and exposes monitoring pitfalls around encoded APC routines."],
    ["WoW64 Internals", "https://wbenny.github.io/2018/11/04/wow64-internals.html", "wbenny", "2018", 5, "WoW64 syscall transition turbo thunk Heaven's Gate internals", "A rigorous map of WoW64 process architecture, system-call transitions, generated thunks, and CPU-mode changes. It is foundational for debugging cross-architecture loaders and understanding why injection code that works in native x64 can fail inside WoW64."],
    ["Reflective DLL Injection", "https://github.com/stephenfewer/ReflectiveDLLInjection", "Stephen Fewer", "Living", 5, "reflective DLL loader PE relocations imports injection", "The original implementation that popularized loading a DLL from memory without the normal LoadLibrary path. Study it as a historical baseline for relocation, import resolution, and self-location, then compare its memory artifacts with modern loader and EDR research."],
    ["PE-sieve", "https://github.com/hasherezade/pe-sieve", "Hasherezade", "Living", 5, "malware scanner hollowing implants PE reconstruction memory", "A mature scanner for injected, replaced, and manually mapped PE images, shellcode, hooks, and in-memory patches. Its code and companion tools are excellent references for learning what imperfect loaders leave behind and how defenders reconstruct those artifacts."],
  ]},
  { id: "malware", kicker: "Reverse real tradecraft", title: "Windows Malware & Loader Analysis", items: [
    ["RONINGLOADER: DragonBreath's Path to PPL Abuse", "https://www.elastic.co/security-labs/roningloader", "Elastic Security Labs", "2025", 5, "RONINGLOADER PPL abuse signed driver WDAC thread pool injection", "Dissects a multi-stage Windows loader that combines a signed kernel driver, custom WDAC policy, PPL abuse, phantom DLLs, and thread-pool injection to suppress multiple security products before launching a gh0st RAT variant. The report connects installer stages, certificate pivots, kernel abuse, user-mode injection, and final payload behavior with public detections."],
    ["BRUSHWORM and BRUSHLOGGER", "https://www.elastic.co/security-labs/brushworm-targets-financial-services", "Elastic Security Labs", "2026", 4, "BRUSHWORM BRUSHLOGGER DLL sideloading keylogger USB propagation", "Analyzes a modular Windows backdoor and companion keylogger recovered from a financial-sector intrusion, including AES-encrypted configuration, scheduled-task persistence, removable-media propagation, extension-based theft, DLL side-loading, keyboard hooks, and iterative development samples. The straightforward code makes the article a useful study in reconstructing capability even when malware is not heavily obfuscated."],
    ["Defeating BazarLoader Anti-Analysis Techniques", "https://unit42.paloaltonetworks.com/bazarloader-anti-analysis-techniques/", "Unit 42", "2022", 5, "BazarLoader anti analysis API hashing control flow obfuscation debugger", "Turns BazarLoader's anti-analysis layers into a repeatable reversing workflow, with scripts and methods for recovering APIs, untangling execution, and neutralizing checks that impede static and dynamic analysis. The focus on reusable analyst techniques rather than campaign indicators makes it valuable beyond the specific malware family."],
    ["CL-UNK-1068 Windows Loader Operations", "https://unit42.paloaltonetworks.com/cl-unk-1068-targets-critical-sectors/", "Unit 42", "2026", 4, "Windows DLL side loading Python loader critical infrastructure malware", "Documents a long-running intrusion set's Windows tooling with detailed attention to Python-based DLL side-loading, malicious loaders, persistence, credential access, and operator utilities. The article provides enough sample and execution context to connect individual loader mechanics to a broader operational chain without reducing the analysis to indicators."],
    ["OXLOADER technical analysis", "https://www.elastic.co/security-labs/oxloader-malware-loader-infostealer", "Elastic Security Labs", "2026", 5, "loader reloc section self modifying MBA anti VM Donut", "A full analysis of a modern loader using CRT-initializer hijacking, self-modifying decryption stubs, control-flow obfuscation, sandbox checks, and .reloc section abuse. It follows execution into Donut-based in-memory delivery and includes detection artifacts, so the article supports both reversing and defensive validation."],
    ["Deep dive on the BLISTER loader", "https://www.elastic.co/blog/deep-dive-on-the-blister-loader", "Elastic Security Labs", "2021", 5, "BLISTER loader signed certificate embedded payload injection", "Analyzes a signed Windows loader that blends malicious logic into legitimate libraries, delays execution, decrypts embedded payloads, and injects them into trusted processes. The combination of loader mechanics, campaign context, and a public configuration extractor makes it a durable case study."],
    ["DarkGate Internals", "https://blog.sekoia.io/darkgate-internals/", "Sekoia.io", "2023", 5, "DarkGate loader APC injection NtTestAlert crypter malware", "Dissects DarkGate's multi-stage execution, configuration, crypter behavior, process injection, and use of NtTestAlert for APC delivery. It is a useful real-world counterpart to the APC internals series because the same mechanism is visible inside an operational malware family."],
    ["BITS and Bytes: analyzing BITSLOTH", "https://www.elastic.co/security-labs/bits-and-bytes-analyzing-bitsloth", "Elastic Security Labs", "2024", 5, "BITSLOTH Windows backdoor BITS C2 handlers reversing", "A careful reverse engineering of a Windows backdoor that uses BITS as its command-and-control channel and exposes dozens of task handlers. It demonstrates how native Windows services shape malware architecture and includes implementation-level details and detections."],
    ["P8LOADER and SPECTRALVIPER", "https://www.elastic.co/security-labs/elastic-charms-spectralviper", "Elastic Security Labs", "2023", 4, "P8LOADER manual PE mapping RuntimeBroker unbacked memory", "Documents an x64 loader that manually maps PE files from disk or memory and a modular backdoor deployed through it. The analysis is concise but valuable for connecting classic section mapping, relocations, and import resolution to the memory telemetry produced by a real intrusion."],
  ]},
  { id: "cves", kicker: "Study complete cases", title: "CVE & Case Studies", items: [
    ["PrintDemon: CVE-2020-1048 and More", "https://windows-internals.com/printdemon-cve-2020-1048/", "Alex Ionescu and Yarden Shafir", "2020", 5, "PrintDemon CVE-2020-1048 spooler LPE persistence arbitrary file write", "A comprehensive investigation of Print Spooler file-writing behavior that produced privilege escalation, persistence, and stealth techniques as well as follow-on fixes. It combines service internals, printer configuration, impersonation, filesystem effects, disclosure timeline, and patch analysis, making it a model multi-impact Windows case study."],
    ["Faxing Your Way to SYSTEM", "https://windows-internals.com/faxing-your-way-to-system/", "Alex Ionescu and Yarden Shafir", "2020", 5, "Windows Fax service SYSTEM privilege escalation DLL loading", "Analyzes a Windows Fax service attack path from service configuration and RPC-accessible behavior through controlled file placement and privileged code loading. The post's strength is its complete treatment of prerequisites, service lifecycle, and remediation, showing how a legacy Windows component can expose a modern local escalation chain without kernel memory corruption."],
    ["CVE-2019-1458: Win32k uninitialized variable", "https://googleprojectzero.blogspot.com/p/rca-cve-2019-1458.html", "Maddie Stone / Project Zero", "2020", 5, "CVE-2019-1458 win32k uninitialized variable bitmap KASLR arbitrary write", "A structured root-cause analysis of an in-the-wild Win32k flaw that records the vulnerable state transition, limited write primitive, public proof of concept, exploit strategy, applicable mitigations, and promising variant-analysis directions. Its explicit separation of root cause, exploitation, structural improvements, and detection makes it an excellent template for studying any Windows zero-day."],
    ["The Windows Registry Adventure: an attack surface review", "https://googleprojectzero.blogspot.com/2024/04/the-windows-registry-adventure-1-registry.html", "Mateusz Jurczyk / Project Zero", "2024", 5, "Windows kernel registry hive fuzzing memory corruption attack surface CVE", "The opening installment of a deep audit of the Windows registry implementation, built from public symbols, reverse engineering, coverage-guided kernel fuzzing, and more than twenty reported issues. It maps the duplicated parser and hive code across boot, kernel, offline, and user-mode components before later exploitation work, giving researchers a rigorous way to bound a complex attack surface."],
    ["CVE-2025-8061: exploiting a Lenovo driver", "https://blog.quarkslab.com/exploiting-lenovo-driver-cve-2025-8061.html", "Quarkslab", "2025", 5, "Lenovo driver LPE reverse engineering CVE-2025-8061", "Follows a vulnerable Lenovo driver from interface reverse engineering through primitive discovery to a working local privilege-escalation chain. The end-to-end methodology makes it useful well beyond this single CVE."],
    ["eneio64.sys physical-memory R/W", "https://xacone.github.io/eneio-driver.html", "xacone", "2023", 5, "CVE-2020-12446 BYOVD HVCI physical memory", "Starts from exposed physical-memory access in eneio64.sys and builds the translation machinery required for useful virtual kernel reads and writes. It also covers HVCI and driver-blocklist constraints that simplified BYOVD writeups often omit."],
    ["AOMEI amwrtdrv raw-disk LPE", "https://afflicted.sh/blog/posts/amwrtdrv-aomei-lpe.html", "afflicted.sh", "2026", 5, "raw disk GPT FAT12 UEFI pre-kernel LPE", "Turns ordinary-user raw-disk access into a pre-kernel execution chain by planting a FAT12 image and redirecting a GPT entry. The post is exceptional for showing how a seemingly narrow driver permission error crosses storage, firmware, and boot trust boundaries."],
    ["SignalRGB: standard user to SYSTEM", "https://afflicted.sh/blog/posts/signalrgb-service-lpe.html", "afflicted.sh", "2026", 4, "service ACL writable binary LocalSystem LPE", "Analyzes a LocalSystem auto-start service whose executable resides in a user-writable directory. It also explains practical replacement and restart constraints, turning a familiar service-permission bug into a complete operational case study."],
    ["SAS CTF Windows 7 challenge explained", "https://securelist.com/sas-ctf-windows-7-challenge-explained/114180/", "Kaspersky Securelist", "2024", 4, "kernel shellcode persistence APT Windows 7 CTF", "Connects a Windows 7 CTF challenge to a kernel-shellcode persistence technique observed in APT activity. The article is valuable for seeing how a real threat technique can be distilled into a reverse-engineering and exploitation exercise."],
    ["CVE-2026-21222: information disclosure", "https://windowsforum.com/threads/cve-2026-21222-windows-kernel-information-disclosure-risk-and-mitigation.400816/", "WindowsForum", "2026", 2, "Windows kernel information disclosure mitigation", "A secondary overview of the reported Windows kernel information-disclosure issue and basic mitigation guidance. Use it as a lead rather than an authoritative technical reference, then confirm details in Microsoft advisories and original research when available."],
  ]},
  { id: "tools", kicker: "Keep beside the debugger", title: "Tools & Technical References", items: [
    ["Secure Kernel Research with LiveCloudKd", "https://windows-internals.com/secure-kernel-research-with-livecloudkd/", "Yarden Shafir", "2024", 5, "LiveCloudKd secure kernel VTL1 debugging memory acquisition", "A practical workflow for using LiveCloudKd to inspect the Secure Kernel and VTL1 state that ordinary kernel debugging cannot directly expose. It explains the acquisition model, symbol use, and analysis boundaries, making the article and tool valuable for validating VBS, KDP, and HyperGuard research against a live system."],
    ["An Exercise in Dynamic Analysis", "https://windows-internals.com/an-exercise-in-dynamic-analysis/", "Yarden Shafir", "2022", 5, "WinDbg dynamic analysis Windows kernel reverse engineering methodology", "A methodology-focused exercise in answering Windows internals questions through live debugging and controlled experiments. Rather than presenting a static conclusion, it demonstrates breakpoint selection, state inspection, hypothesis refinement, and verification, which makes it a reusable guide for researching undocumented kernel behavior safely."],
    ["Troubleshooting a System Crash", "https://windows-internals.com/troubleshooting-a-system-crash/", "Yarden Shafir", "2024", 4, "Windows crash dump WinDbg bugcheck root cause driver debugging", "Walks through a real Windows crash investigation using dump analysis, stack and object inspection, and progressive hypothesis testing. It belongs in the reference table because it teaches how to establish causality from debugger evidence instead of stopping at the blamed module name reported by automated crash tools."],
    ["I/O Rings: When One I/O Operation Is Not Enough", "https://windows-internals.com/i-o-rings-when-one-i-o-operation-is-not-enough/", "Yarden Shafir", "2021", 5, "Windows I/O rings internals asynchronous I/O API structures", "The original deep introduction to Windows I/O rings, reconstructing the user-mode API, submission and completion queues, registered resources, and kernel implementation. It is the conceptual reference needed before reading later exploitation primitives, because it explains the legitimate object lifecycle and invariants that corruption violates."],
    ["One Year to I/O Ring: What Changed?", "https://windows-internals.com/one-year-to-i-o-ring-what-changed/", "Yarden Shafir", "2022", 5, "Windows I/O rings version changes API kernel structures", "Compares the I/O ring implementation across a year of Windows releases, documenting API growth, structure changes, registration behavior, and security-relevant differences. The version-aware analysis prevents researchers from applying an early proof of concept blindly to newer builds and demonstrates how to maintain undocumented internals research over time."],
    ["IoRing vs io_uring", "https://windows-internals.com/ioring-vs-io_uring-a-comparison-of-windows-and-linux-implementations/", "Yarden Shafir", "2021", 4, "Windows IoRing Linux io_uring architecture comparison asynchronous I/O", "A careful architectural comparison of Windows I/O rings and Linux io_uring, covering queue ownership, registration, operation submission, completion, and kernel trust boundaries. The cross-platform framing clarifies which security assumptions are inherent to ring-based asynchronous I/O and which are specific implementation choices in Windows."],
    ["WinAFL", "https://github.com/googleprojectzero/winafl", "Google Project Zero", "Living", 5, "Windows coverage guided fuzzing DynamoRIO TinyInst persistent mode", "The established AFL-derived coverage-guided fuzzer for Windows binaries, with DynamoRIO and TinyInst instrumentation, persistent and in-app modes, crash minimization, and extensive real-world vulnerability credits. Its documentation and harness examples make it a primary starting point for reproducible user-mode fuzzing rather than a generic link collection."],
    ["Sandbox Attack Surface Analysis Tools", "https://github.com/googleprojectzero/sandbox-attacksurface-analysis-tools", "James Forshaw / Project Zero", "Living", 5, "Windows sandbox attack surface COM RPC named pipes object manager tokens", "A maintained suite for enumerating and analyzing Windows sandbox attack surface across object-manager namespaces, processes, tokens, services, RPC, COM, network endpoints, and accessible resources. The tools embody the methodology behind several Project Zero sandbox-escape investigations and are especially useful for comparing effective policy with the boundary a product claims to enforce."],
    ["TinyInst", "https://github.com/googleprojectzero/TinyInst", "Google Project Zero", "Living", 5, "dynamic instrumentation coverage Windows fuzzing debugger harness", "A lightweight dynamic instrumentation library used for coverage collection and fuzzing on Windows and other platforms, with debugger-based control and a deliberately smaller architecture than full binary-instrumentation frameworks. It is the relevant primary reference when WinAFL or Jackalope uses TinyInst-backed coverage and when a researcher needs to understand instrumentation behavior rather than treat it as a black box."],
    ["Jackalope", "https://github.com/googleprojectzero/Jackalope", "Ivan Fratric / Project Zero", "Living", 5, "binary coverage guided fuzzer Windows TinyInst mutators persistent", "A modern binary coverage-guided fuzzer designed around TinyInst, supporting Windows targets, custom mutators, persistent execution, corpus management, and distributed workflows. The repository includes the actual engine and operational documentation, making it a high-signal alternative for targets that do not fit source-based fuzzing or WinAFL's harness model."],
    ["PerfView and TraceEvent", "https://github.com/microsoft/perfview", "Microsoft", "Living", 5, "ETW TraceEvent ETL stacks kernel providers performance diagnostics", "Microsoft's open-source ETW collection and analysis stack, including the TraceEvent library used to create sessions, enable kernel and user providers, decode events, capture stacks, and process ETL data programmatically. It is a primary implementation reference for researchers who need to verify telemetry behavior rather than infer it from an EDR interface."],
    ["Awesome Windows CTF", "https://zaratec.io/awesome-windows-ctf/", "zaratec", "Living", 5, "Windows CTF pwn challenges writeups kernel heap usermode Hyper-V", "A Windows-specific CTF index that separates challenges by competition, target layer, and exploitation topic, with direct links to artifacts and writeups. It is now used as a discovery graph for this catalog; individual challenges are promoted only after their technical content is independently checked."],
    ["Windows Malware Analysis Training, Volume 1", "https://github.com/hasherezade/malware_training_vol1", "Hasherezade", "Living", 5, "malware analysis PE processes WoW64 shellcode loaders hooking exercises", "A freely licensed Windows malware-analysis curriculum with slides and hands-on exercises covering PE files, processes, WoW64, shellcode, loaders, injection, hooking, persistence, and evasion. It is unusually valuable because concepts are paired with code and analysis tasks rather than presented as a tool checklist."],
    ["Driver Buddy Reloaded", "https://github.com/VoidSec/DriverBuddyReloaded", "VoidSec", "Living", 5, "IDA plugin Windows driver IOCTL WDM WDF reverse engineering", "An IDA Pro plugin that labels WDM/WDF structures, finds dispatch routines and device names, decodes IOCTLs, identifies pool tags, and flags dangerous functions or opcodes. It accelerates triage without hiding the analysis steps, which makes it suitable for both learning and repeated driver audits."],
    ["vulnerable-drivers", "https://github.com/KeServiceDescriptorTable/vulnerable-drivers", "KeServiceDescriptorTable", "Living", 4, "vulnerable Windows drivers samples research corpus", "A broad driver corpus linked from many recent LOLDrivers records and intended for vulnerability research. Its value is coverage and sample availability; provenance and exploitability still need to be established from each driver's advisory, issue, or independent reversing work."],
    ["prefetch-tool", "https://github.com/exploits-forsale/prefetch-tool", "exploits.forsale", "2024", 5, "KASLR prefetch side channel assembly timing", "A focused proof of concept for resolving the Windows kernel base through prefetch timing. Read the assembly-level timing loop alongside the 24H2 exploit research to connect the side-channel theory with hardware-specific reliability limits."],
    ["Vergilius Project", "https://www.vergiliusproject.com/", "Vergilius", "Living", 5, "Windows kernel structures symbols offsets", "A searchable catalog of tens of thousands of undocumented Windows kernel structures across builds and architectures. It is invaluable for quickly comparing layouts, but build-specific offsets should still be validated against symbols and the target binary."],
    ["System Informer: ntexapi.h", "https://github.com/winsiderss/systeminformer/blob/master/phnt/include/ntexapi.h", "System Informer / phnt", "Living", 5, "NtQuerySystemInformation SYSTEM_INFORMATION_CLASS Native API", "The phnt declarations for Native system-information APIs and the SYSTEM_INFORMATION_CLASS family. Use it for accurate enum values and structure layouts missing from the public SDK, while remembering these interfaces can change between Windows builds."],
    ["System Informer: ntpsapi.h", "https://github.com/winsiderss/systeminformer/blob/master/phnt/include/ntpsapi.h", "System Informer / phnt", "Living", 5, "Native process thread APIs information classes", "The phnt process-and-thread header covering Native process, thread, job, and related information classes. It is the quickest source for checking structures expected by NtQueryInformationProcess and NtQueryInformationThread before confirming behavior in symbols or disassembly."],
    ["NtDoc: PROCESSINFOCLASS", "https://ntdoc.m417z.com/processinfoclass", "NtDoc", "Living", 5, "PROCESSINFOCLASS NtQueryInformationProcess documentation", "A browsable, cross-linked reference for process information classes used by NtQueryInformationProcess and NtSetInformationProcess. It summarizes buffer types, access requirements, and version notes, making it a convenient companion to phnt headers."],
    ["IoRingReadWritePrimitive", "https://github.com/yardenshafir/IoRingReadWritePrimitive", "Yarden Shafir", "2022", 5, "Windows 11 I/O rings kernel read write primitive", "Shows how a limited kernel write or increment can be transformed into a full read/write primitive through Windows I/O rings. The small implementation is an excellent post-exploitation reference for understanding the user/kernel objects and corruption required by the technique."],
    ["DrvEye", "https://github.com/0xDbgMan/DrvEye", "0xDbgMan", "2026", 4, "driver triage IOCTL symlink certificates BYOVD", "Automates static triage of Windows drivers by surfacing IOCTLs, symbolic links, certificates, imports, and other exploitation-relevant features. Its BYOVD-oriented workflow is useful for prioritization, but findings still require manual reverse engineering and validation."],
    ["Windows Kernel Exploits archive", "https://github.com/SecWiki/windows-kernel-exploits", "SecWiki", "Living", 4, "Windows kernel CVE privilege escalation exploit archive", "A large historical archive of public Windows kernel privilege-escalation exploits organized by vulnerability and platform. It is useful for comparative study and lab reproduction, though many samples target obsolete builds and should never be assumed safe or production-ready."],
    ["awesome-fuzzing", "https://github.com/secfigo/awesome-fuzzing", "secfigo", "Living", 4, "fuzzing root cause analysis exploit development resources", "A broad curated index covering fuzzers, papers, courses, root-cause analysis, and exploit development. Use it to choose a domain-specific starting point rather than reading linearly, and check linked projects for current maintenance status."],
    ["vss-fr2system", "https://github.com/sailay1996/vss-fr2system", "sailay1996", "2026", 3, "VSS file read SYSTEM Windows technique", "A compact research repository exploring a Windows VSS/file-read-to-SYSTEM path. The upstream description is intentionally sparse, so treat the code as a lab artifact to reverse engineer and validate rather than as documented guidance."],
  ]},
] as const;
const total = groups.reduce((sum, group) => sum + group.items.length, 0);
const stars = (rating: number) => `${"★".repeat(rating)}${"☆".repeat(5 - rating)}`;
---

<div class="research-index" data-research-index>
  <div class="research-index__search">
    <label for="research-search">Search the index</label>
    <input id="research-search" type="search" placeholder="Try: KASLR, EDR, pool, CVE, I/O rings..." autocomplete="off" data-research-search />
    <p data-research-status aria-live="polite">{researchers.length} researchers and {total} resources</p>
  </div>
  <aside class="research-index__rubric" aria-label="Reading priority rubric">
    <strong>Reading priority</strong>
    <span><b>★★★★★</b> foundational / must-read</span><span><b>★★★★☆</b> strong practical depth</span><span><b>★★★☆☆</b> useful or specialized</span><span><b>★★☆☆☆</b> supplemental / secondary</span>
  </aside>
  <nav class="research-index__jump" aria-label="Jump to a research area">
    <a href="#researchers-heading">Researchers</a>
    {groups.map((group) => <a href={`#${group.id}-heading`}>{group.title}</a>)}
  </nav>
  <section data-index-group aria-labelledby="researchers-heading">
    <div class="research-index__heading"><div><p class="research-index__kicker">People to follow</p><h2 id="researchers-heading">Researchers &amp; Blogs</h2></div><span>{researchers.length} entries</span></div>
    <div class="research-index__table-wrap"><table><thead><tr><th>Researcher</th><th>Blog</th><th>Primary focus</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      {researchers.map(([name, site, url, profile, focus]) => <tr data-index-row data-kind="researcher" data-searchable={`${name} ${site} ${focus}`}><td><a href={profile} target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">{name}</a></td><td><a href={url} target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">{site}</a></td><td>{focus}</td></tr>)}
    </tbody></table></div><p class="research-index__none" data-group-empty hidden>No matching researchers.</p>
  </section>
  {groups.map((group) => <section id={`${group.id}-section`} data-index-group aria-labelledby={`${group.id}-heading`}>
    <div class="research-index__heading"><div><p class="research-index__kicker">{group.kicker}</p><h2 id={`${group.id}-heading`}>{group.title}</h2></div><span>{group.items.length} entries</span></div>
    <div class="research-index__table-wrap"><table class="resource-table"><thead><tr><th>Resource</th><th>Year</th><th>Priority</th><th>Why it matters</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      {group.items.map(([title, url, source, year, rating, tags, note]) => <tr data-index-row data-kind="resource" data-searchable={`${title} ${source} ${year} ${tags} ${note}`}><td><a href={url} target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">{title}</a><small>{source}</small></td><td><span class="research-index__year">{year}</span></td><td><span class="research-index__stars" title={`${rating} out of 5 reading priority`} aria-label={`${rating} out of 5 reading priority`}>{stars(rating)}</span></td><td>{note}</td></tr>)}
    </tbody></table></div><p class="research-index__none" data-group-empty hidden>No matching resources in this section.</p>
  </section>)}
</div>

<script>
  document.querySelectorAll<HTMLElement>("[data-research-index]").forEach((root) => {
    const input = root.querySelector<HTMLInputElement>("[data-research-search]");
    const status = root.querySelector<HTMLElement>("[data-research-status]");
    const sections = [...root.querySelectorAll<HTMLElement>("[data-index-group]")];
    input?.addEventListener("input", () => {
      const query = input.value.trim().toLowerCase(); let researchers = 0; let resources = 0;
      sections.forEach((section) => { let visible = 0; section.querySelectorAll<HTMLElement>("[data-index-row]").forEach((row) => { const match = (row.dataset.searchable ?? "").toLowerCase().includes(query); row.hidden = !match; if (match) { visible++; row.dataset.kind === "researcher" ? researchers++ : resources++; } }); const empty = section.querySelector<HTMLElement>("[data-group-empty]"); if (empty) empty.hidden = visible !== 0; });
      if (status) status.textContent = `${researchers} researchers and ${resources} resources`;
    });
  });
</script>

<style>
  .research-index{display:grid;gap:var(--space-2xl);margin-top:var(--space-xl)}.research-index__search{position:sticky;top:4.75rem;z-index:5;display:grid;grid-template-columns:auto minmax(16rem,1fr) auto;align-items:center;gap:var(--space-md);padding:var(--space-md);border:1px solid var(--color-border);border-radius:var(--radius-xl);background:color-mix(in srgb,var(--color-bg-primary) 94%,transparent);box-shadow:var(--shadow-md);backdrop-filter:blur(12px)}.research-index__search label{font-weight:700}.research-index__search input{width:100%;min-height:2.75rem;border:1px solid var(--color-border);border-radius:var(--radius-lg);background:var(--color-bg-primary);color:var(--color-text-primary);padding:.65rem .85rem;font:inherit}.research-index__search p{margin:0;color:var(--color-text-secondary);font-size:.8125rem;white-space:nowrap}.research-index__rubric{display:flex;flex-wrap:wrap;gap:.65rem 1.25rem;padding:var(--space-md);border:1px solid var(--color-border);border-radius:var(--radius-xl);background:var(--color-bg-secondary);font-size:.82rem}.research-index__rubric strong{width:100%}.research-index__rubric b,.research-index__stars{color:#d69e2e;letter-spacing:.04em}.research-index__jump{display:flex;flex-wrap:wrap;gap:.5rem;margin-top:calc(var(--space-xl)*-1)}.research-index__jump a{border:1px solid var(--color-border);border-radius:var(--radius-full);background:var(--color-bg-secondary);padding:.4rem .7rem;font-size:.78rem;text-decoration:none}.research-index__jump a:hover{border-color:var(--color-text-secondary)}.research-index section{display:grid;gap:var(--space-md);scroll-margin-top:6rem}.research-index__heading{display:flex;align-items:end;justify-content:space-between;gap:var(--space-md)}.research-index__heading h2,.research-index__kicker{margin:0}.research-index__kicker{color:var(--color-text-secondary);font-family:var(--font-mono);font-size:.72rem;letter-spacing:.1em;text-transform:uppercase}.research-index__heading>span{color:var(--color-text-secondary);font-size:.8125rem}.research-index__table-wrap{overflow-x:auto;border:1px solid var(--color-border);border-radius:var(--radius-xl)}.research-index table{width:100%;min-width:54rem;border-collapse:collapse;font-size:.9rem}.research-index .resource-table{min-width:68rem}.research-index th,.research-index td{padding:.9rem 1rem;border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border);text-align:left;vertical-align:top}.research-index th{background:var(--color-bg-secondary);color:var(--color-text-secondary);font-size:.75rem;letter-spacing:.06em;text-transform:uppercase}.research-index tbody tr:last-child td{border-bottom:0}.research-index tbody tr:hover{background:var(--color-bg-secondary)}.research-index td:first-child{width:25%;font-weight:650}.resource-table td:nth-child(2){width:7%}.resource-table td:nth-child(3){width:12%;white-space:nowrap}.research-index a{color:var(--color-text-primary);text-underline-offset:.2rem}.research-index small{display:block;margin-top:.25rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);font-weight:400}.research-index__year{font-family:var(--font-mono);font-size:.78rem}.research-index__none{margin:0;padding:var(--space-lg);border:1px dashed var(--color-border);border-radius:var(--radius-lg);color:var(--color-text-secondary);text-align:center}[data-index-row][hidden]{display:none}@media(max-width:48rem){.research-index__search{position:static;grid-template-columns:1fr}.research-index__search p{white-space:normal}}
</style>
